 The City Diary
																																																																																		The decomposed body of an unidentified, middle-aged man was found on Chetla Road on Monday afternoon. According to police, the man, in a T-shirt and jeans, appeared to have died more than 48 hours before the body was discovered around 3pm on Monday. There were deep injury marks on the head and the police suspect he could have been bludgeoned to death. The body was sent to SSKM Hospital for post-mortem.																																																		Bapi Das, a thief who was arrested in Bijpur on Sunday night, fled while being taken from the police station to the Barrackpore additional chief judicial magistrates court on Monday morning. According to police, Bapi fled from the police van which had gone to Naihati police station to collect criminals. Senior police officers said a probe had been ordered.																																																		Sunita Rai, 30, was found hanging on Monday morning in a house on Bipin Bihari Ganguly Street, in the Muchipara police station area. Police suspect she was depressed about an ailment and had committed suicide. Her husband, Ranjit Rai, a factory labourer, found the body. No suicide note was found. The victim was originally from Bihar and had come to Calcutta for treatment. The body was sent for post-mortem. 																																																		The body of Shontu Dey, 22, was found on the campus of Medical College Hospital, near Gate No. 1, around 2.30pm on Monday. He was taken to the emergency department of the hospital, where he was declared dead. A preliminary investigation revealed that he was a resident of the Muchipara area. The body was sent for post-mortem.																																																		A crude bomb under a garbage heap close to the land registration office at Chiria More, in Barrackpore, burst on Monday morning, sparking panic. According to police, a ragpicker found the bomb in a can and as he tried to throw it away, it burst, ripping off the ragpickers right arm. He was shifted to BN Bose Hospital, where his condition was said to be critical.																																																		Traders are facing trouble in depositing trade enlistment renewal fees of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) in banks, as some employees are refusing to accept the sum on the plea of mismatching bar codes.																																																								unicipal commissioner Alapan Bandyopadhyay said banks get a commission for rendering the service on behalf of the CMC. Chief manager (licence) Bhaskar Ghosh said there are several thousand cases where a bill that had been refused by a bank was accepted by another. Moreover, the unreadable bar codes can be deciphered by the code-reading machine in the civic headquarters.							TO ROTARY CLUB OF COSSIPORE for organising a mega health and eye check-up camp at Calcutta Girls College, Janbazar
